<DOC><DOCNO> AP880504-0327 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1413EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0037 05-04 0169</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0037,0173</SECOND><HEAD>London Shares Off</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with closing figures</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices declined Wednesday after thegovernment said it would refer the Kuwaiti government's acquisitionof a British Petroleum Co. PLC stake to the monopolies commission.   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished down12.5 The index's best level was 2 points up, hit as the trading daybegan.   Volume was a moderate 427.4 million shares, compared withTuesday's 335 million shares.   Wall Street's lower opening added fuel to an already decliningLondon market, dealers said.   Traders said the bearish tone was set early in the session whenthe Department of Trade and Industry announced that it would referthe Kuwait government's purchase of a 22 percent stake in BP to theMergers and Monopolies Commission to determine whether it is in thepublic interest.   The referral ``completely depressed market sentiment and thatwas it for the rest of the day,'' said Mark Kane, a trader withKitkat and Aitken Ltd.</TEXT></DOC>